Here we are 4 weeks in!!! This is what changing out bad habits for good habits looks like. This is what being held accountable looks like! The scale is only a fraction of the picture here. Ivan couldn’t walk around the block due to his lower back hurting in week 1 and struggled with his sleep. Let’s look at where we are 1 month in…….he is sleeping like a baby, has a ton more energy, can perform brisk walks each day getting in cardio and a ton more movement. His mood is elevated, his blood pressure is down, he has a healthy glow about him now and a bounce in his step! He is 3 X as strong physically & mentally in the gym than he was a month ago. His body fat is down 📉 and his muscle is up ⬆️ And as a friend and mate, he’s now on the path to a much healthier and fulfilled life. I guarantee the more he is on this journey the more the people around him will benefit too ❤️💪🏽 it goes deeper than just looking better. Remembering my Grandad and the unimaginable sacrifices he made with thousands of other men! 25 yrs old 1941, WW2 in Egypt, 7th armoured division better known as the Desert rats. The division fought in most of the major battles of the Western Desert campaign, was then engaged in the Tunisian campaign, and this was followed by the participation in the Italian campaign. It was then withdrawn from Italy and dispatched to the United Kingdom, to prepare for Operation Overlord. In June 1944, it landed in France and subsequently fought across western Europe and ended the war in Kiel and Hamburg, Germany.

A humble farmer from Ballabeg in the Isle of Man, thrust into a blood bath for 7 years in his 20s. Didn’t grow up with movies and television like we did. He’d never stepped off the island before having to take on the weight of what I can’t even begin to imagine. We often go through life not acknowledging the elders around us, not knowing their story and how much stronger and wiser they are than us. He was the best grandad ever, always cracking jokes, constantly laughing at himself and brining a light hearted mood to the room. Many won’t believe me that he played football with me into his 80s and was always out walking for miles everyday into his 90s. It’s only been the last few years that I have begun to realise just how mentally and physically strong he was. 

It’s him that without realising embedded this fascination with nutrition and exposing the modern diet. Up until he passed away peacefully in 2016 at 100years old he was still in better health than most! And I know it was from a lifetime of eating real food, always being outside, walking, lifting and never giving up, he never quit not once! A mentality that is so rare and so hard to find in this modern world. God I would love to have his strength! A true warrior and good, good man! Forever in my heart and mind ❤️
